"The scanner in the next room carried a new bulletin. The van’s registration had entered a regional lookout, and the subject alert had been relayed nationally. No confirmed recovery had been announced. No location had been attached to them yet.\n\nYet.\n\nJulie closed the aluminum case and checked both latches. The 136 sealed files remained primary. The 47 incomplete files remained incomplete. The 311 excluded files remained absent. The ninth checksum remained unexplained beyond its role in the post-archive object. The raw K-17 observations remained sensitive and unresolved.\n\nThe administrator-token board returned to Elias.\n\nThe signed recovery cartridge went into a tamper bag beneath Julie’s name in the custody log.\n\nThe limited duplicate remained separate in the locked storage cabinet.\n\nThey had enough to accuse Arthur Vance of authorizing the Payload 88 bridge.\n\nThey had enough to show a Northbridge endpoint in the operational chain and a second synchronization scheduled for 07:08.\n\nThey did not have Sterling’s command, the contents of the Northbridge communications, the identity of the field team’s sponsor, or proof of what had happened at Relay K-17 since the last sensor contact.\n\nMarcus read the summary Julie had written.\n\n“We take this to an inspector general.”\n\n“The raw case exposes military collection and active sensor locations,” Julie said.\n\n“Then the cartridge.”\n\n“Classified incident record carried out of a protected facility by three people already named in a sabotage alert.”\n\n“The duplicate omits the raw telemetry.”\n\n“It also omits context Apex will demand. Vance’s certificate proves his authority. It does not prove who directed him. Northbridge’s certificate proves a legitimate contractor endpoint participated. It does not reveal the message.”\n\nMarcus looked toward the sealed garage. “An honest official can understand that.”\n\n“After detaining us, separating us, and taking every original into custody.”\n\n“That is procedure.”\n\n“Yes.” Julie met his eyes. “It does not require corruption to give Vance time. The first recipient will have an armed-insider bulletin, classified material, a damaged custody path, and three injured fugitives. Securing us will come before understanding us.”\n\nElias pulled the blanket tighter. “And Apex will provide the explanation while we sit in separate rooms.”\n\n“A public dump?” Marcus asked.\n\n“Reveals sensors, collection methods, and troop locations. It could put people in danger and make the files look exactly like stolen material used in an attack.”\n\n“The press?”\n\n“Same problem with less secure handling.”\n\nMarcus looked at the 07:08 entry.\n\n“What we have can survive a technical examination,” Julie said. “It may not survive the first hostile explanation. The live buffer and signing chain might.”\n\n“Might.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\nThe battery-backed clock advanced to 06:25.\n\nOutside the closed bay, a truck passed through the alley without slowing. Its tires hissed over wet pavement and faded toward the commercial street.\n\nMarcus listened until the sound was gone.\n\nThen he looked at Julie.\n\n“Who do we trust?”\n\nJulie looked at the sealed case, Elias’s bandaged hand, and the blood beginning to show through the edge of Marcus’s dressing.\n\n“No one yet.”\n\n---\n\n# Chapter 11 - Going Offensive\n\nDecommissioned Communications Cutout\n Fairfax County, Virginia\n 06:25 Eastern Daylight Time\n\nThe battery-backed clock advanced to 06:25:11.\n\nNo one moved.\n\nStatic breathed through the analog scanner. One fluorescent tube above the equipment table flickered at an interval too irregular to count. Beyond the wall, PCF-27 remained inside the service bay with its known plate, white contractor paint, and disconnected fleet module. The van was hidden from the alley. Nothing else about it had disappeared.\n\nMarcus sat with his right leg extended beneath the table. Blood had begun to show through the lower edge of the dressing above his ear, a narrow dark line entering the gray at his temple. The cold pack around his thigh had gone soft. Cloth tape held the split heel of his boot in rough alignment, not enough to make the foot reliable. Each breath lifted only the upper part of his chest.\n\nElias still wore the wool blanket around his shoulders. His bandaged index finger rested against the administrator-token board in his lap as if contact alone could keep him from losing it.\n\nJulie’s wrapped wrist lay against her body. The rigid plastic strip beneath the elastic had reduced the movement and taken most of the use of her right hand with it. The aluminum case stood closed at the end of the table. The tamper-bagged recovery cartridge and the paper custody log lay beside it in the order she had recorded them. The limited derivative remained sealed inside the locked storage cabinet.\n\nForty-two minutes and forty-nine seconds remained before the Northbridge window.\n\nMarcus looked at the clock. “Then what?”\n\nJulie heard the question beneath the question. If there was no recipient they could reach now, what did the word yet require them to do?\n\n“We stop looking for someone to hand this to before seven-oh-eight,” she said.\n\nElias’s gaze lifted. “That sounds very much like deciding no one is honest.”\n\n“It isn’t.” Julie pulled the paper summary toward her with her left hand. “An inspector general could be honest. FBI counterintelligence could be honest. The first officers who stop that van could be doing exactly what they should.”\n\n“Detain us,” Marcus said.\n\n“Yes. Separate us. Secure the case. Put Elias under protective custody because the alert calls him a hostage. Treat you as an armed accomplice and me as the person who corrupted Argus.”\n\nMarcus’s mouth tightened at the word armed. They possessed no firearm. The bulletin did not need one to exist.\n\nJulie continued. “Then someone finds a cleared technical team. Someone determines jurisdiction. Someone asks Apex for the system record. Vance gets to explain every file before anyone compares the certificate chains.”\n\n“The inspector general could order a hold,” Marcus said.\n\n“After intake. After authentication. After they know which inspector general owns the program. Northbridge’s synchronization will be gone before the first custody receipt is signed.”\n\nElias looked toward the locked storage cabinet. “A reporter?”\n\n“Cannot safely publish the raw material and cannot authenticate it in forty minutes. If we give them the limited copy, Northbridge says its endpoint is part of a legitimate Apex contract. If we give them the case, we expose collection locations and the unresolved K-17 sensor record.”\n\n“A congressional channel,” Marcus said.\n\nJulie looked at the Northbridge certificate still open on the old workstation. “Sterling sits inside the oversight structure we would be asking for help. That does not make every staff member part of this. It means we cannot know where the warning goes before the evidence is secured.”\n\nThe scanner broke through the static with a county unit acknowledging the national lookout. No location followed. No confirmed sighting.\n\nMarcus waited until the transmission ended. “So the problem isn’t trust.”\n\n“The problem is sequence.” Julie touched the paper summary. “The first honest action is still custody. Understanding comes later.”\n\n“And seven-oh-eight comes first,” Elias said.\n\nJulie looked at the battery clock.\n\nThe three evidence sources could survive examination. They could not create the one record that did not yet exist.\n\n“We make the missing evidence,” she said.\n\nMarcus shifted in the chair. Pain stopped the movement halfway. “Define that before you turn it into a mission.”\n\nJulie took the pen in her left hand.\n\n“Northbridge Secure Suite Four receives a hardware-authenticated K-seventeen Phase B synchronization at seven-oh-eight. The suite holds the live session envelope for no more than ninety seconds. While it exists, the Northbridge endpoint, the external signer, the routing state, the hardware time, and the message buffer are all linked.”\n\n“Ciphertext,” Marcus said.\n\n“Probably.”\n\n“So we may leave without the message.”\n\n“We may leave with proof of who authenticated an exchange into the K-seventeen operational channel. Or proof that the signer belongs to someone we have not considered. Or proof that the exchange is less important than we think.”\n\nElias watched her write. “The full external certificate matters more than the name printed on it.”\n\nMarcus looked at him.\n\n“The certificate gives us the signing authority, device serial, trust chain, and the entity to which the device is registered,” Elias said. “The hardware signature shows that device actually answered the session challenge. It does not prove who was physically holding it.”\n\nJulie wrote that distinction beneath the objective.\n\nREGISTERED AUTHORITY IS NOT PHYSICAL POSSESSION.\n\n“If the certificate resolves to Sterling?” Marcus asked.\n\n“It still proves the device, not his hand,” Julie said. “If the content or routing adds his direction, we preserve it. We do not assume it.”\n\n“And if it resolves to Northbridge counsel, an Apex executive, or a field contractor?”\n\n“We preserve that too.”\n\n“Who has the device now?” Marcus asked.\n\n“The metadata does not say,” Elias replied.\n\nMarcus watched the pen move. “K-seventeen?”\n\n“Still unresolved. The field team’s last confirmed position is more than an hour old. The synchronization profile does not tell us whether they reached the relay, failed, withdrew, or are waiting for another instruction.”\n\nHe nodded once. The plan had not improved yet. It had only become honest.\n\nJulie wrote the objective in one line.\n\nREACH NORTHBRIDGE SECURE SUITE 4 BEFORE 07:08. CAPTURE THE LIVE BUFFER, ROUTING STATE, FULL SIGNING CHAIN, HARDWARE SIGNATURE, SESSION TIME, AND K17-PHASE-B LINKAGE. LEAVE.\n\nMarcus read it.\n\n“That is an intelligence requirement,” he said. “Not an entry plan.”\n\n“No.”\n\n“Where is the suite?”\n\nJulie turned the workstation toward Elias. The Northbridge endpoint certificate filled the old display. They had examined the organizational subject and trust fingerprints. The lower fields remained collapsed beneath the service policy.\n\n“Registered equipment location,” she said.\n\nElias used his left hand on the trackball. The first movement overshot the field. He corrected and expanded the certificate details.\n\nMost of the entries were administrative: contract tenant, certification authority, inspection cycle, hardware class. Near the bottom, a location extension appeared beside the service-access profile.\n\nREGISTERED EQUIPMENT SITE: FENWICK ANNEX\n TENANT: NORTHBRIDGE STRATEGIC INITIATIVES\n SERVICE LOCALITY: L STREET NW / WASHINGTON, DC\n FACILITIES ENTRY: REAR SERVICE VESTIBULE\n SECURE DOMAIN: WSS-4\n\nMarcus leaned forward, then stopped when his ribs objected.\n\n“The Fenwick Building,” he said.\n\n“You know it?” Julie asked.\n\n“I know the public side. L Street between Seventeenth and Eighteenth. Narrow commercial building, stone front, private offices above a ground-floor lobby. I attended two policy working groups there before Northbridge took the upper floors.”\n\n“Secure annex?”\n\n“Never saw it. There is a service alley behind the block and a landlord entrance off it. Deliveries, maintenance, cleaning crews. The public elevators are inside the L Street lobby.”\n\nNothing about the building, the public offices, or the existence of a secure contractor suite was illegal. The certificate made it a location. It did not make it a crime scene.\n\nElias expanded the next field.\n\nCONTROLLER PROFILE: APX SECURE FACILITY 4.2\n MAINTENANCE ENROLLMENT: LOCAL / ESCORTED\n PRE-SESSION DIAGNOSTIC WINDOW: ENABLED\n LOCAL AUDIT INTERFACE: REQUIRED\n\nHe went still.\n\n“What?” Julie asked.\n\n“I helped design that profile.”\n\nMarcus looked at him. “For Northbridge?”\n\n“No. For Apex-certified contractor suites. Places that need compartmented communications without turning an ordinary office building into a federal facility.” Elias pulled the blanket away from his hands. “The landlord controls the outer doors. The tenant controller begins after the service vestibule. Public-office badges and secure-suite access are separate.”\n\n“Current codes?” Julie asked.\n\n“I do not know them.”\n\n“Current staff?”\n\n“No.”\n\n“Cameras, guards, floor plan?”\n\n“I know the minimum design requirements. I do not know what Northbridge installed or changed.”\n\n“Good.”\n\nElias looked at her. “That is not usually the response to ignorance.”\n\n“It is when the alternative is pretending.”\n\nShe pointed to the diagnostic-window field. “Explain.”\n\n“A hardware-signer session creates a short local maintenance period before the scheduled exchange. A legitimately enrolled technician can test the suite certificate, the local clock, and the incident recorder without seeing message content. The enrollment has to happen at the building. The external signer may be somewhere else, but the Northbridge suite will be active and monitored by someone inside by seven-oh-eight.”\n\n“Remote access?” Marcus asked.\n\n“Not for this controller. That is the point. The service vestibule reads a tenant work order, the landlord guard verifies the contractor, and a Northbridge sponsor acknowledges the request. Then the controller can issue an escorted temporary session. The enrollment, the module serial, and every incident export become local audit events.”\n\n“Can you make one?”\n\n“No.” Elias answered before Marcus finished the question. “I can make something that looks like a work order. I can use the correct tenant identifier, service-call format, and diagnostic reason. The live system will know the ticket does not exist if anyone checks it.”\n\n“How long before it knows?”\n\n“That depends on the guard, the sponsor, and whether the controller is already in pre-session mode. It may reject us immediately.”\n\nJulie looked at the service profile. “What does it buy?”\n\n“A reason for someone inside to open the conversation. Perhaps a temporary intake screen. Seconds.”\n\n“Not a door.”\n\n“Not by itself.”\n\nMarcus’s gaze remained on the certificate. “Where is the live buffer?”\n\n“In volatile memory inside the communications controller. The operator sees a session status, not the full envelope. A protected audit port can export the session envelope to incident media if a local maintenance session is active.”\n\n“Export what, exactly?” Julie asked.\n\nElias counted with his left thumb against his fingers. “Northbridge suite certificate. External signing certificate. Challenge and response. Hardware signature. Hardware time reference. Session identifier. Routing receipts. Task profile. Ciphertext buffer. The order in which they appeared.”\n\n“Does it decrypt?”\n\n“No.”\n\n“Does it copy the rest of Northbridge?”\n\n“No. It is deliberately narrow.”\n\n“Can it open the secure suite?”\n\n“No.”\n\nMarcus sat back. “So we still need physical access to the room containing the port.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\n“And someone has to know when the external certificate is actually present.”\n\nElias looked at the screen.\n\nJulie saw the answer before he gave it.\n\n“The session can show open before the full chain loads,” he said. “The Northbridge certificate presents first. The external device may answer several seconds later. If you capture too early, you get Northbridge talking to an unidentified trust fingerprint. If you wait until the acknowledgment completes, the buffer may begin purging.”\n\n“You can tell the difference,” Julie said.\n\n“I know the state sequence.”\n\n“I can write it down.”\n\n“No.” The word came quietly. “You can memorize the labels. You will not know which delay is normal and which means the signer failed to present. The current software may not use the same colors or wording. The audit state is in the event order.”\n\nMarcus looked from Elias to Julie. “Remote instructions are out.”\n\nElias’s bandaged finger pressed against the edge of the circuit board.\n\nJulie said, “You stay with Marcus.”\n\nHis eyes lifted.\n\n“I can take the module. You tell me the sequence now.”\n\n“You just heard why that will not work.”\n\n“I heard why it is less reliable.”\n\n“It may be useless.”\n\n“The alert still describes you as a hostage. The next camera that records you entering a Washington secure facility beside me will end that protection.”\n\n“I know.”\n\n“You may be arrested there. Your board may be seized. The incident capture may incriminate you again. You may not be able to walk back out on that hip.”\n\n“I know.”\n\n“I cannot promise I can get you out.”\n\nElias looked down at the board. The secure element that contradicted Vance’s deployment record sat beneath his thumb. His right hand trembled once and stopped when he closed it around the edge.\n\nJulie waited.\n\n“You can refuse,” she said.\n\n“I know that too.”\n\n“Then refuse if that is your decision.”\n\nThe scanner hissed. A truck changed gears somewhere beyond the alley. Marcus did not interrupt.\n\nElias drew the blanket tighter around his shoulders, then let it fall behind him onto the chair.\n\n“You will not recognize the complete signer state,” he said. “And you will not know whether the incident export has preserved the event order until it seals.”\n\n“That is an explanation.”\n\n“I am going.”\n\nHis voice remained frightened. He did not make it louder to disguise that.\n\nJulie looked at him for another second. “Voluntarily?”\n\n“Yes.”\n\nShe opened the custody log to the next line and wrote the time.\n\nMarcus watched her record it. “Now define everyone else.”\n\nJulie put down the pen.\n\n“You keep the originals.”\n\n“The case stays outside the target?”\n\n“The case never enters the building. Neither does the recovery cartridge or the custody log.”\n\n“And me?”\n\n“You stay with them and the van.”\n\nMarcus’s expression hardened. “I can still control an entrance.”\n\n“You cannot run, your balance is unreliable, and a deep breath is an argument. I am not putting you in a controlled corridor because you dislike sitting outside.”\n\n“I can move far enough to pull you through a door.”\n\n“Once.”\n\n“That may be the useful one.”\n\nJulie met his eyes. “The useful one is protecting the only evidence we already have.”\n\nThe words landed harder than an order would have. The aluminum case stood between them, intact because Marcus had refused to surrender it in Reston and carried it through every barrier after.\n\nHe looked away first.\n\n“Where is the van?” he asked.\n\n“Close enough for extraction. Not at the service door.”\n\n“It is a known vehicle.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\n“If a plate reader catches it in Washington, response moves toward Northbridge whether they know the connection or not.”\n\n“We use it because it is what we have. We enter through ordinary contractor traffic, park off the direct approach, and accept that every minute after the first camera is borrowed.”\n\n“Who drives?”\n\n“I do.”\n\n“With that wrist.”\n\n“With my left hand and the wheel braced against my forearm. You cannot work the pedals reliably.”\n\nMarcus did not argue with the leg. “Route?”\n\n“Rear industrial exit. One short diversion before we turn east. No toll road. Ordinary speed. Arlington Boulevard, then the Roosevelt Bridge unless traffic forces another choice.”\n\n“Final approach?”\n\n“You direct it from memory. We do not circle the target. We do not search for a perfect camera gap that does not exist.”\n\n“Exit?”\n\n“Same service route if it remains open. Ordinary fire stair to the public lobby if it does not. No deeper movement through Northbridge.”\n\n“And if the service intake refuses?”\n\n“We leave.”\n\n“If the signer never appears?”\n\n“We leave.”\n\n“If the message proves less than expected?”\n\n“We preserve exactly what it proves and leave.”\n\n“If police arrive?”\n\nJulie looked at both men. “We do not turn honest officers acting on a false alert into casualties. No firearms. No hostage-taking. No ramming a way out. If the only exit requires hurting someone who is not trying to kill us, the operation ends.”\n\nMarcus studied her. “You are allowing arrest.”\n\n“I am refusing murder as an escape plan.”\n\n“And Northbridge security?”\n\n“We do not attack them for doing their jobs. We use the service process. If deception fails, we disengage.”\n\nElias looked toward the workstation. “The local port is inside the secure domain.”\n\n“Then we get there without making civilians pay for our evidence.”\n\nMarcus continued testing the edges. “Search scope?”\n\n“The live session only. No desks. No personnel files. No Northbridge archive. No attempt to take the communications controller.”\n\n“Sterling?”\n\n“We are not going there to find him.”\n\n“If he is there?”\n\n“We do not touch him.”\n\nMarcus nodded once.\n\n“Destruction?”\n\n“None. The suite remains operational.”\n\n“Disclosure?”\n\n“No upload. No public release. We capture, preserve, and leave.”\n\n“What time do I pull you?”\n\n“Seven-ten.”\n\nElias looked at the clock. “The buffer should be gone by then.”\n\n“The extra time is for us to get out, not to analyze it.”\n\n“And if you are thirty seconds from sealing the export?” Marcus asked.\n\n“Seven-ten.”\n\nHe held her gaze, measuring whether she believed her own abort condition.\n\nJulie did. She did not know whether she would obey it. Command required setting the line before fear and proximity made every additional second feel necessary.\n\nMarcus shifted the cold pack aside. “Civilian load?”\n\n“Landlord security, cleaners, early policy staff, whoever Northbridge brought in for the regional crisis. We assume every person we see knows nothing about Payload Eighty-Eight.”\n\n“That includes the person carrying the signer.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\nElias said, “Even if the certificate belongs to Sterling’s office?”\n\n“Even then. A certificate is evidence. It is not permission to decide what the person holding it deserves.”\n\nSilence followed.\n\nMarcus reached for the paper objective and turned it so he could read it again.\n\n“Then we need a way to capture without risking the originals,” he said.\n\nJulie opened the locked storage cabinet.\n\nThe derivative module remained inside its numbered antistatic envelope. The sealed partition held the recovery record, restored label map, provenance decision, Payload 88 index, checksum history, and the critical bridge fragments. It did not hold the bulk raw telemetry or the sensitive K-17 geography.\n\nElias examined the module through the clear side of the envelope. “It supports two separately sealed partitions.”\n\n“You are sure?” Julie asked.\n\n“The enclosure is standard field-evidence media. Partition one seals against its own manifest. Partition two can remain blank without changing the first.”\n\n“Can the Northbridge audit port write to it?”\n\n“If the controller still follows the 4.2 profile. The incident interface accepts encrypted removable media and writes a self-contained session package. It should not care what is on the other partition.”\n\n“Should.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\nJulie returned to the workstation.\n\nAt 06:37:02, she broke the numbered envelope seal and recorded the action. Elias mounted the module through the hardware write blocker and verified the derivative partition. Its hashes matched the values entered in the paper log.\n\nHe created no new copy.\n\nInstead, he used the module’s physical management utility to expose the unused second partition. The first remained hardware-locked and read-only. The second appeared as an empty encrypted incident volume with a separate serial and no files.\n\nPARTITION A: SEALED DERIVATIVE\n INTEGRITY: VERIFIED\n WRITE STATE: LOCKED\n\nPARTITION B: INCIDENT CAPTURE\n CONTENT: EMPTY\n WRITE STATE: ARMED ON LOCAL DEVICE\n\nJulie recorded both states, the module serial, the wall-clock time, and the fact that the workstation clock remained wrong by eleven days. She had Elias verify Partition A again after the change.\n\nMATCH.\n\nOnly then did she remove the module and seal it inside a fresh antistatic sleeve. The storage cabinet had no second numbered evidence envelope. She closed the sleeve with tamper tape from the medical cabinet and wrote the module serial across the seam.\n\n“The sealed copy travels into Northbridge,” Marcus said.\n\n“The originals stay with you.”\n\n“If you lose the module?”\n\n“We lose the limited duplicate and whatever we capture. The case, board record, and recovery cartridge remain.”\n\n“The board goes inside,” he said.\n\n"